qas.question: To what distinct feature of the area does Emerald City refer?
Since Seattle is near Alaska, what is the city called?
From what company does Seattle get its nickname Jet City?
What did Seattle call itself at the time of the Goodwill Games?

context: From 1869 until 1982, Seattle was known as the "Queen City". Seattle's current official nickname is the "<a0_0>Emerald City<a0_0/>", the result of a contest held in 1981; the reference is to the lush <a1_0>evergreen forests<a1_0/> of the area. Seattle is also referred to informally as the "<a2_0>Gateway to Alaska<a2_0/>" for being the nearest major city in the contiguous US to Alaska, "Rain City" for its frequent cloudy and rainy weather, and "Jet City" from the local influence of <a3_0>Boeing<a3_0/>. The city has two official slogans or mottos: "The City of Flowers", meant to encourage the planting of flowers to beautify the city, and "<a4_0>The City of Goodwill<a4_0/>", adopted prior to the 1990 Goodwill Games. Seattle residents are known as Seattleites.
